# Cursor Rules for Vue UI Library Development

## 1. Code Structure
- The `<template>` section **must always** come before the `<script>` section in Vue components.
- Use **single-file components (SFCs)** for Vue components, ensuring proper separation of concerns.

## 2. Best Practices for Vue 3 & TypeScript
- Always use **Composition API** (`setup()`) instead of Options API.
- Define **props with TypeScript interfaces** for strict type safety.
- Use `defineProps` and `defineEmits` instead of `props` and `emit` from the setup function.
- Avoid `any` type; prefer **explicit types** for props, events, and function parameters.
- Always use `defineOptions({ name: "ComponentName" })` for component naming.
- Use named functions over arrow functions.

## 3. Handling Text & Translations
- **Never hardcode human-readable text inside components**.
- All text content **must be provided via `props` or `slots`** to allow translation in other projects.
- Default props for text values should be **empty strings (`""`)** or **undefined**, never hardcoded text.

## 4. Styling & Structure
- Styling for components **must rely on custom SCSS**.
- Always use `<style scoped lang="scss"></style>` inside Vue components.
- Refer to the following file for guidance on writing custom SCSS:
  - **`src/assets/design-system-stories/approach.mdx`**
- Use SCSS variables from the following directory:
  - **`src/assets/styles`**
- **Never use inline styles** unless absolutely necessary.
- Prefer `class` bindings (`:class="{ active: isActive }"`) over direct `style` bindings.

## 5. Code Conciseness
- Avoid unnecessary comments; **comments should explain "why," not "what"**.
- **No unused imports or variables**; enforce via ESLint.
- Always use **script setup** syntax to keep the code concise.

## 6. Events & Reusability
- Emit events instead of modifying parent data directly.
- Prefer `v-model` for two-way bindings where applicable.

## 7. Component and story consistency
- When refactoring elements of a component also update the appropriate values for that components stories.

## 8. Testing
- Prefer using 'data-test' attribute for targeting elements over classes. Add to the component if required.
- We a helper you can use to target elements by 'data-test': wrapper.findby("trigger-btn")
- When refactoring to fix a failing test, do not refactor the component. Adapt the test to match component behavior or check its behavior is valid first.


---

## Example of a Well-Formatted Component
```vue
<template>
  <button :class="['btn', variant]" @click="handleClick">
    <slot />
  </button>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
defineOptions({ name: "MyButton" });

interface Props {
  variant?: "primary" | "secondary";
}

const props = defineProps<Props>();
const emit = defineEmits<{
  (event: "click"): void;
}>();

function handleClick() {
  emit("click");
};
</script>

<style scoped lang="scss">
.btn {
   padding: var(--size-base-8) var(--size-base-16);
   font-size: var(--size-text-base);
   background-color: var(--gray-10);
   border-radius: var(--border-radius-8);

   .primary {
      background-color: var(--primary-color);
   }

   .secondary {
      color: var(--purple-80);
      background-color: var(--purple-20);
   }
}
</style>
